replyContent: There was an issue with the "back" button but an update has now been released so that you can use it to exit the game once again. (The "home" button on your Android device can always be used to exit any app, if you find yourself in a similar situation in the future.)

It shouldn't need to disable the screen lock and make internet connections.
replyContent: It is to prevent the screen from dimming during gameplay. If the game is paused the device is allowed to dim the screen after a while. The Internet permission is just there because Adobe AIR requires it, JezzBall Classic doesn't use Internet at all right now (current game version is 2.0.1 when this was written).

Great I bought it, now can you develop Maxwell's Maniac? It's like the twin brother of JezzBall. Also where are the sounds and how about showing an optional on-screen cursor?
replyContent: Not sure if a Maxwell mod will appear in the game but sounds are now available. You are able to display a "direction toggler" that show the current deploy direction and you can instruct the game to always show the deployment flag. Since 2.0.0 a mouse cursor can also be shown (even if your device has no mouse). See the controls config menu.

This is a good Jezzball clone, very faithful and with easy-to use controls. I just wish the balls went bonk bonk.
replyContent: Sound is now available. By default the atoms only go bonk when they collide with each other but it's possible to enable bouncing sounds against walls as well in the new audio config menu. Wall collisions are silent by default because when you get a few atoms in the chamber there will be a wall collision every single second.
